  "prompt": "Can an isosceles triangle be a right triangle? Why or why not?",
  "response": "Yes, an isosceles triangle can be a right triangle. \n\nAn isosceles triangle is defined as a triangle with at least two sides of equal length. A right triangle is defined as a triangle that has one angle equal to 90 degrees. \n\nFor an isosceles triangle to also be a right triangle, it must have one 90-degree angle and two sides of equal length. This is possible if the two equal sides are the legs of the right triangle, forming the 90-degree angle where they meet. In this case, the triangle would be both isosceles and right. An example of such a triangle is a 45-45-90 triangle, where the two legs are equal and the hypotenuse is \\(\\sqrt{2}\\) times the length of each leg.",
